      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Try to run a system command or OS command using python code",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "BFkh7qDpM2zFKW-D0kI6x",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1170.068603127786,
      "y": -10570.794139068526,
      "width": 1276,
      "height": 525,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b9U",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 60481389,
      "version": 732,
      "versionNonce": 595329698,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776967947935,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "using os and subprocess we can connect with our base terminal\n\nimport os\ndir(os)\n\nos.system(\"date\") -> similar to date command in our linux terminal\nos.system(\"ls\")\nos.system(\"hostname\") -> 192.168.1.7 \n                         0 -> this 0 means command is succesful there is no error, if error it will give any random \n                                number 1 or anything\nip = os.system(\"hostname\") -> 192.168.1.7\nip -> 0\n\nin Linux terminal\n\ndate -> it will print date time of system and it will return us the exit code of this command\necho $? -> 0\ndate -datajakfghajshf -> error\necho $? -> 1 or any other random number\ndate2 \necho $? -> 127 -> means command not found",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "using os and subprocess we can connect with our base terminal\n\nimport os\ndir(os)\n\nos.system(\"date\") -> similar to date command in our linux terminal\nos.system(\"ls\")\nos.system(\"hostname\") -> 192.168.1.7 \n                         0 -> this 0 means command is succesful there is no error, if error it will give any random \n                                number 1 or anything\nip = os.system(\"hostname\") -> 192.168.1.7\nip -> 0\n\nin Linux terminal\n\ndate -> it will print date time of system and it will return us the exit code of this command\necho $? -> 0\ndate -datajakfghajshf -> error\necho $? -> 1 or any other random number\ndate2 \necho $? -> 127 -> means command not found",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "onYOpQVacExLaf1FsnITK",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1165.9813200715355,
      "y": -10014.2971060348,
      "width": 1155,
      "height": 1275,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b9V",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1489286253,
      "version": 1782,
      "versionNonce": 367767550,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776969376520,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "import os -> os is our base Operating system\nimport subprocess as sp\n\ndir(os)\ndate = os.system(date) -> this will give log of entire thing that we are doing here date\ndate -> 0 -> this is giving command is successful or not\n\nwhen we have to print the log of command that is running we use os.system \n\nBut when we have to save the output or capture the output we use subprocess module\ndir(sp)\nsp.getoutput(\"date\") -> it will give date\ndate = sp.getoutput(\"date\") -> it will not give anything\ndate -> it will give date\n\ndate = sp.getstatusoutput(\"date\") -> it will not give anything\ndate -> (exitcode, date & time) -> first will always be a integer and second will always be a string \n                                no matter which command we are running.\ntype(date[0]) -> int\ntype(date[1]) -> Str\n\na = sp.getstatusoutput(\"echo $?\")\na -> (0, \"0\")\n \nSome command need human intervention in between like Yes or No\nalways figure out ways and give that whole command so that our script can run withour human interventions\nso that our script will not stopped in between, so whenever we write a script we write in a way such\nthat it can run without human intervention\n\napt-get upgrade -y -> -y means yes no need to ask in between\n\n\nram = sp.getstatusoutput(\"vm_stat\") -> vm_stat is used in mac in place of free for RAM\nram\n\nalways first check output of command, how our data looks like, then script accordingly\n\ncompression = sp.getstatusoutput(\"vm_stat\") \nprint(compression)\nint(compression[1].split('Compression:')[1].lstrip().split('.')[0])\n\n\nstatus, output = sp.getstatusoutput(\"top -l 1\") -> -l 1 → run 1 iteration and exit \n                                                    (equivalent to Linux -n 1)\nload1, load2, load3 = output.split('Load Avg:')[1].split('\\n')[0].split(',')\n>>> load1 = float(load1.strip())\n>>> load1\n2.87\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "import os -> os is our base Operating system\nimport subprocess as sp\n\ndir(os)\ndate = os.system(date) -> this will give log of entire thing that we are doing here date\ndate -> 0 -> this is giving command is successful or not\n\nwhen we have to print the log of command that is running we use os.system \n\nBut when we have to save the output or capture the output we use subprocess module\ndir(sp)\nsp.getoutput(\"date\") -> it will give date\ndate = sp.getoutput(\"date\") -> it will not give anything\ndate -> it will give date\n\ndate = sp.getstatusoutput(\"date\") -> it will not give anything\ndate -> (exitcode, date & time) -> first will always be a integer and second will always be a string \n                                no matter which command we are running.\ntype(date[0]) -> int\ntype(date[1]) -> Str\n\na = sp.getstatusoutput(\"echo $?\")\na -> (0, \"0\")\n \nSome command need human intervention in between like Yes or No\nalways figure out ways and give that whole command so that our script can run withour human interventions\nso that our script will not stopped in between, so whenever we write a script we write in a way such\nthat it can run without human intervention\n\napt-get upgrade -y -> -y means yes no need to ask in between\n\n\nram = sp.getstatusoutput(\"vm_stat\") -> vm_stat is used in mac in place of free for RAM\nram\n\nalways first check output of command, how our data looks like, then script accordingly\n\ncompression = sp.getstatusoutput(\"vm_stat\") \nprint(compression)\nint(compression[1].split('Compression:')[1].lstrip().split('.')[0])\n\n\nstatus, output = sp.getstatusoutput(\"top -l 1\") -> -l 1 → run 1 iteration and exit \n                                                    (equivalent to Linux -n 1)\nload1, load2, load3 = output.split('Load Avg:')[1].split('\\n')[0].split(',')\n>>> load1 = float(load1.strip())\n>>> load1\n2.87\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
